The ILBE Pack is designed to carry loads up to 120 pounds but at the same time distribute the weight evenly so it's comfortable to wear.

The back of the pack offers the ability to customize your pack with MOLLE accessories by using MOLLE webbing and it includes a compartment on the outside to hold a hydration system.

title: For Sale:  Piece of History - 1942 Springfield Armory M1 Garand war relic
postcontent:
EDITED TO ADD: I cannot match CMP pricing, so please don't ask. Make a reasonable market-priced offer.

Field grade M1 Garand in .30 (civilian .30-06). Springfield Armory receiver, dated from May 1942. Springfield barrel dated 1951. Good strong bore. Trigger group and op rod are Winchester; this is typical of a USGI re-arsenaled rifle. Stock marked RRA (Red River Arsenal work done after WWII). Wood is walnut and has seen some use - pics were taken before cleaning and a light coat of BLO (proper finish for this rifle). Stock looks nicer in person, but I want you to see all the marks and wear. Comes with certificate of authenticity, hard case, 4 (four) 8-round clips (yes, clips), user guide, chamber flag.

More pics here: https://picasaweb.google.com/REDACTEDREDACTED1/SAGarand?authkey=Gv1sRgCIuB5Jr3qa2PEA

With re-importation of these no longer allowed from South Korea and other allies, these are getting harder and harder to find, especially the WWII vintage rifles. 

Asking $1300 o.b.o., FTF Charleston area. This is on my C&R, so I need to see SC DL or Mil ID with orders, SC CWP, or we can go through an FFL dealer in Summerville - I'll pay the fee.

INFORMATION FROM WIKIPEDIA

When the LWRC Six8 was being developed, Alliant Techsystems was contracted to develop a new 6.8x43mm round for the weapon. Unlike smaller commercial firms, ATK is a large ammunition supplier that delivers products for the U.S. Army, so it had large resources and manufacturing capabilities at its disposal. Commercial cartridges varied in case capacity and thickness, but LWRC wanted a thick and durable case for military uses. A 90 gr (5.8 g) load was developed specifically for a high muzzle velocity and low felt recoil from the Six8's 8.5 in (220 mm) barrel. Effective range would be over 300 yd (274 m) and the bullet would still have enough energy to penetrate intermediate barriers. Three 90 gr loads were constructed for testing that included Gold Dot, Monolithic Hollow Point, and FMJ. The Gold Dot bullet was selected with a .035 in (0.89 mm) jacket and a bonded core. The propellant was designed for reduced muzzle flash stable performance at temperatures between -29.2 to 125.6 degrees F. Muzzle velocity averaged at a 200 ft/s (61 m/s) difference at the required temperature extremes from the 8.5 in barrel. From a 24 in (610 mm) barrel, the round produced a group of 1.56 in (40 mm) at 200 yd (183 m).[16]

title: For Sale:  1889 Remington 12ga, Grade 3, Damascus
postcontent: 1889 Remington 12ga, Grade 3, Damascus. The Remington Arms Co. Model 1889 was madein seven grades. The lowest grade, Grade 1, had decarbonized steel barrels. A Grade 2 had twist steel barrels and a Grade 3 had Damascus barrels. Grades 1, 2, and 3 had no engraving and half-pistol grip stocks. Higher grades, 4, 5, 6, and 7 had increasing amounts of engraving, finer wood and checkering, and finer Damascus barrels. The Model 1889 was dropped in 1908, but a few in the 259,xxx range were in the final sale of all Remington break open shotguns, on hand and in process, to Norvell-Shapleigh of StLouis, on February 3, 1910. title: For Sale:  Parker Bros GH2, 12ga
postcontent: This is a very collectible 1885 Parker Bros GH2, 12ga shotgun. Please note the right side hammer is missing. The Grade 2 production started about 1875, before the grading system was adopted and it sold for $80 (a 80 Dollar grade). As Parker introduced the named grades they named Grade 2 guns E, F, G, H, EH and GH. The GH and EH describes Grade 2 hammerless Parkers, the other names describe Grade 2 hammer guns. These names were based on various gauge and stock configurations. It was a popular gun for the owner that wanted a gun with more adornment that the average gun and was willing to pay about $20 more for a gun that looked better and was well balanced. The Grade 2 had a higher quality of American walnut which has some figure. Most Grade 2 guns have Damascus or Parker Special Steel barrels. They were significantly better engraved than the lower grade guns. Quail, ducks, snipe and woodcock are common figures in the engraving of the frame sides and bottom; the forend latch and screw heads are also engraved. The checkering was deeper and finer than lower grade Parkers. After about 1880, the hard rubber dogs head butt plate and a white metal shied behind the top tang became standard on the Grade 2. Because of the added embellishments, it was very popular with Parker customers. Ejectors were an option on GH grade. These guns with ejectors (GHE) are desirable to collectors and can add as much as 50% to their collector value. Production numbers*: Lifter Hammer 4,555 Top Lever Hammer 7,582 Hammerless 31,778 Item G-8272-8 We have additional higher resolution pictures of this item available upon request. Call REDACTED or come by Green Country Arms & Pawn in Tulsa, OK, (9075 E 31st St, Tulsa, OK). Be sure to mention that you saw our ad on Armslist. We can also ship to a FFL dealer. Shipping is $20 for all hand guns and $40 for long guns in the lower 48 states. We do NOT ship to CA. We will ship to NY, CO, CT or any other state within the restrictions of those states. If you have a question, please ask. Payment can be made using a credit card (NO Am. Ex.), by phone or with postal money order (upon clearing). We are currently not accepting personal checks. title: For Sale:  Standard Pressure Short Barrel Low Flash Heavy .38 Special Ammo - 158 gr. Soft Lead SWC-HC (850fps/M.E. 253 ft. lbs.) - 20 Round Box
postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=110

Due to customer demand, we've developed this defensive 38SPL ammo. Our customers wanted some devastating 38SPL loads that would fill the following criteria. 

1. It won't hurt older/fragile/alloy revolvers. (Non +P)
2. Is effective as a "fight stopper" through the use of proper bullets. 
3. Is more powerful than typical/standard, weak 38SPL ammo.
4. Generate much less recoil than our +P 38SPL ammo.
5. Is flash suppressed.

Buffalo Bore is introducing these three different heavy, yet standard pressure loadings for 38 SPL. These offerings are loaded at standard pressure, but they are much more powerful than normal 38SPL ammo. These loads will not harm older more fragile revolvers. So, these loads are safe for use in ANY 38 SPL revolver, provided it is in normal working condition. As stated above, the "POWER" level of these loads is really closer to a typical +P power level, but the pressure is standard. We are able to develop these powerful standard pressure loads with modern non-canister powders. Again, these loads recoil far less than our +P 38 SPL ammo. 

All three of these loads are flash suppressed, so firing them in the dark wont blind you. We use flash suppressed powder in our defensive ammo, in the loadings we can, because over 90% of all civilian shootings in America, occur in low light, when the criminal element is at work. We don't want you blinded by your own gunfire after the first shot. 

Item 20C utilizes the same 158gr. very soft lead cast, SWC-HC gas checked bullet, we load in our +P 38 SPL ammo. It is designed to expand and then penetrate quite deep. (Approx. 14 inches in human tissue) This bullet is gas checked and will NOT lead your barrel. Note the below velocities that I recorded out of my personal revolvers- NOT TEST BARRELS!

1. S&W mod. 60, 2 inch barrel - 854 fps (256 ft. lbs.)
2. S&W mod. 66, 2.5 inch barrel - 871 fps (266 ft. lbs.)
3. Ruger SP101, 3 inch barrel - 930 fps (303 ft. lbs.)
4. S&W Mt. Gun, 4 inch barrel - 979 fps (336 ft. lbs.)
